240
00:15:15,555 --> 00:15:17,381
Please, l want to read clear through
the alphabet.

241
00:15:17,640 --> 00:15:19,596
l want to know everything in the
world.

242
00:15:20,766 --> 00:15:27,594
Well, all right. Only, do something
for me, won't you?

243
00:15:27,852 --> 00:15:29,132
Take another book too. Here:

244
00:15:29,394 --> 00:15:34,267
"When Knighthood Was in
Flower". Just for fun. ls Saturday.

245
00:15:34,522 --> 00:15:36,976
l'll have a headache thinking about
you wrestling with

246
00:15:37,231 --> 00:15:38,974
"The Anatomy of Melancholy"
all weekend.

247
00:15:39,232 --> 00:15:40,772
Will you?

248
00:15:41,024 --> 00:15:42,896
Yes, ma'am.

249
00:15:54,529 --> 00:15:56,236
A little more to the left,
Mr. Crackenbach.

250
00:15:56,488 --> 00:15:59,653
You think l want to see me clothes
hanging with your wash up there!

251
00:15:59,906 --> 00:16:03,356
Don't you forget to fix mine,
Mr. Crackenbach!

252
00:16:03,617 --> 00:16:06,284
Maybe you'd like to come up here and
fix it yourselves.

253
00:16:06,535 --> 00:16:08,775
And thas just what you'll be doing
if you don't shut up!

254
00:16:09,036 --> 00:16:11,110
Mr. Crackenbachl...

255
00:16:32,920 --> 00:16:39,085
...a wheelbarrow, through streets
broad and narrow, crying cockles

256
00:16:39,339 --> 00:16:42,042
and mussels alive alive oh.

257
00:16:42,298 --> 00:16:42,795
l won! l won!

258
00:16:43,049 --> 00:16:45,124
Well, now, l wouldn't be too sure
about that if l was you.

259
00:16:45,383 --> 00:16:47,422
But l did. l got it open before you
finished and thas the rule.

260
00:16:47,676 --> 00:16:49,751
But l came up one flight two steps
at a time before l remembered.

261
00:16:50,010 --> 00:16:50,923
Don't that make a difference?

262
00:16:51,177 --> 00:16:51,841
No, sir. The rules say that

263
00:16:52,095 --> 00:16:53,422
And in a manner of speaking, you
never did stop me at all,

264
00:16:53,679 --> 00:16:55,337
because my heart kept right
on singing.

265
00:16:55,554 --> 00:16:57,095
Papa, you're joking.

266
00:16:57,346 --> 00:16:59,551
Well, l guess l'll let you get away
with it this time, Prima Donna.

267
00:16:59,806 --> 00:17:01,263
And where's your beautiful Mama?

268
00:17:01,515 --> 00:17:01,799
Finishing the hall.

269
00:17:02,057 --> 00:17:03,929
She must be on the top floor or
she'd have heard you.

270
00:17:04,183 --> 00:17:06,174
Well, in that case, why aren't you
getting busy?

271
00:17:06,434 --> 00:17:08,010
Why aren't you laying out my
clothes?

272
00:17:08,268 --> 00:17:11,764
Oh, Papa, you always make fun. You
know you haven't any more clothes.

273
00:17:12,019 --> 00:17:13,761
Haven't any more clothes, huh?
Whas this?

274
00:17:14,019 --> 00:17:15,182
A tie.
- And this?

275
00:17:15,437 --> 00:17:16,468
A dickie.
- And this?

276
00:17:16,729 --> 00:17:18,009
An apron.
- Well, them's clothes, ain't they?

277
00:17:18,271 --> 00:17:19,895
And you'd better be getting that
apron ironed too.

278
00:17:20,147 --> 00:17:21,771
Oh, Papa, you've got a job for
tonight?

279
00:17:22,023 --> 00:17:22,888
You see the palm of that hand?

280
00:17:23,149 --> 00:17:24,392
Thas right where l got the world
tonight.

281
00:17:24,648 --> 00:17:25,395
Where's the job, Papa?

282
00:17:25,649 --> 00:17:26,644
Klompers. A big wedding party.

283
00:17:26,900 --> 00:17:29,650
And you know something, Prima Donna?
There'll be plenty of tips.

284
00:17:29,901 --> 00:17:31,229
singing or waiting?
- Both.

285
00:17:31,485 --> 00:17:34,319
Oh, maybe tonighll be it. Maybe
tonight he'll be there.

286
00:17:34,570 --> 00:17:35,518
The impresario.

287
00:17:35,779 --> 00:17:38,150
And he'll hear you sing, and he'll
put you on the stage!

288
00:17:38,405 --> 00:17:39,684
And why not? Ain't l the Brooklyn
Thrush?

289
00:17:39,946 --> 00:17:41,226
Oh, Papa!

290
00:17:41,489 --> 00:17:44,441
And now you'd better be getting my
apron ironed.

291
00:17:44,699 --> 00:17:46,406
Have it in a jiffy, Papa. The
coffee's on.

292
00:17:46,658 --> 00:17:51,946
Thas my Prima Donna. Early one
morning, l heard a maiden singing.

293
00:17:52,202 --> 00:17:54,442
Ear... Pst! Pst!

294
00:17:54,702 --> 00:17:57,904
Oh, Papa, l can't sing.

295
00:17:58,162 --> 00:18:00,070
Come on, now, you're holding up the
singing!

296
00:18:00,330 --> 00:18:04,028
"Oh, don't deceive me, oh, don't you
leave me."

297
00:18:04,290 --> 00:18:06,661
And better singing l never did hear.

298
00:18:06,916 --> 00:18:08,741
l love to iron for you, Papa.

299
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:09,615
You know, something?

300
00:18:09,875 --> 00:18:12,199
A day like this is just like
somebody gave you a present.

301
00:18:12,460 --> 00:18:13,917
Everything just right.

302
00:18:14,169 --> 00:18:17,287
l wonder what people did before they
invented coffee.

303
00:18:17,545 --> 00:18:21,078
Oh, this sure could be a fine world,
if...

304
00:18:21,339 --> 00:18:25,001
Hey, you know something, Prima
Donna?

305
00:18:25,256 --> 00:18:27,295
You're going to make somebody a
mighty fine wife, some day.

306
00:18:27,549 --> 00:18:28,711
Oh, Papa.

307
00:18:28,966 --> 00:18:32,796
And mighty pretty, too. That is, if
your nose doesn't grow crooked.

308
00:18:33,051 --> 00:18:35,837
Could it really? Honest?

309
00:18:36,095 --> 00:18:39,212
Oh, no! ls the prettiest nose in
all Brooklyn.

310
00:18:39,470 --> 00:18:41,426
Oh, Papa, it isn't.
- who says it isn't?

311
00:18:41,680 --> 00:18:43,636
You just tell me who said it and
l'll take care of 'em.

312
00:18:43,889 --> 00:18:45,347
Papa, you're crazy!

313
00:18:45,598 --> 00:18:46,760
And you know something else?

314
00:18:47,015 --> 00:18:48,425
You're not going to be ironing like
this when that impresario

315
00:18:48,683 --> 00:18:49,263
comes along.

316
00:18:49,517 --> 00:18:51,259
Things are going to be different
around here, you wait and see!

317
00:18:51,517 --> 00:18:52,217
Yes, Papa.

318
00:18:52,476 --> 00:18:55,047
Hey, whas the wish you wish the
most when our ship comes sailing in?

319
00:18:55,310 --> 00:18:57,385
Well, it already came true.

320
00:18:57,644 --> 00:18:59,435
What is it? Come on and tell me.

321
00:18:59,687 --> 00:19:04,927
Well, l wished that when you came
home today, you wouldn't be sick.

322
00:19:10,191 --> 00:19:11,981
Oh, who told you to call it "sick"
baby?

323
00:19:12,234 --> 00:19:15,565
Ah, you shouldn't waste your wishes
on things like that!

324
00:19:15,819 --> 00:19:19,731
You should be saving 'em, for a silk
dress or something.

325
00:19:19,987 --> 00:19:21,730
Haven't you got a better wish than
that?

326
00:19:21,988 --> 00:19:23,528
Well...
- Come on!

327
00:19:24,113 --> 00:19:26,437
Well, l hope Mama won't be too mad
with Aunt Sissy.

328
00:19:26,698 --> 00:19:28,405
What about Aunt Sissy?

329
00:19:28,657 --> 00:19:32,818
She's gone and got herself another
husband. Again!

330
00:19:33,076 --> 00:19:38,446
No! Oh, oh, no! Gee, if there isn't
a woman for you!

331
00:19:38,702 --> 00:19:40,694
Hey, what did -what did your Manna
say?

332
00:19:40,953 --> 00:19:43,657
Well, she didn't like it.
- l can imagine that.

333
00:19:45,164 --> 00:19:48,661
Couldn't you say something to her?
Not to be too mad to Aunt Sissy?

334
00:19:49,541 --> 00:19:51,366
That l could, Prima Donna, and that
l will.

335
00:19:51,625 --> 00:19:52,822
Oh, thank you, Papa.

336
00:19:53,084 --> 00:19:58,075
Now, haven't you got just one little
wish for yourself? Just one wish?

337
00:19:58,335 --> 00:19:59,995
Just for you.

338
00:20:00,712 --> 00:20:04,292
Well... Did you see it, Papa?
- What?

339
00:20:04,547 --> 00:20:06,704
Out the window. Our tree. They've
killed it!

340
00:20:11,049 --> 00:20:13,965
Well, would you look at that now?

341
00:20:14,217 --> 00:20:16,292
They didn't have any right to kill
it, did they, Papa?

342
00:20:18,177 --> 00:20:21,212
Oh now, wait a minute. They didn't
kill it.

343
00:20:21,470 --> 00:20:22,928
Why they couldn't kill that tree.

344
00:20:23,178 --> 00:20:24,008
Honest?

345
00:20:24,262 --> 00:20:25,127
Oh, why sure, baby.

346
00:20:25,388 --> 00:20:27,877
Don't tell me that tree's gonna lay
down and die that easy.

347
00:20:28,139 --> 00:20:31,553
Look at that tree, see where is
coming from?

348
00:20:31,807 --> 00:20:34,214
Right up out of the cement.
Didn't nobody plant it.

349
00:20:34,475 --> 00:20:37,047
lt didn't ask the cement could it
grow.

350
00:20:37,310 --> 00:20:38,340
lt just couldn't help growing so
much it

351
00:20:38,601 --> 00:20:40,011
pushed that old cement right
out of the way.

352
00:20:40,811 --> 00:20:42,185
Why, when you're busting with
something like that,

353
00:20:42,436 --> 00:20:43,550
can't anybody help it.

354
00:20:43,812 --> 00:20:48,222
Like... Like that little old bird
right up there. Listen to him.

355
00:20:52,858 --> 00:20:54,516
He didn't ask anybody could he sing,

356
00:20:54,775 --> 00:20:56,517
and he certainly didn't take
any lessons.

357
00:20:56,775 --> 00:20:59,977
He's so full of singing, is just
got to bust out someplace.

358
00:21:00,235 --> 00:21:02,476
Why they could cut that old tree
right down to the ground

359
00:21:02,737 --> 00:21:05,061
and a root would push up
someplace else in the cement.

360
00:21:05,321 --> 00:21:07,112
You wait till Spring, Prima Donna
and you'll see.

361
00:21:09,781 --> 00:21:11,902
Well, this ain't winning the family
bread, huh?

362
00:21:14,908 --> 00:21:19,034
Come on, ain't you got one nice
little wish just for yourself?

363
00:21:20,369 --> 00:21:24,944
No, Papa. l just...
- Just what?

364
00:21:25,203 --> 00:21:28,119
l just love you so much, Papa.

365
00:21:28,372 --> 00:21:33,659
Well, what do you know.

366
00:21:33,916 --> 00:21:40,199
Listen, if l make a lot of tips
tonight, you know what l'm gonna do?

367
00:21:40,460 --> 00:21:41,834
What Papa?

368
00:21:42,085 --> 00:21:45,702
l'm gonna put two bucks on the nose
of a horse l know is running Monday.

369
00:21:45,962 --> 00:21:48,878
And l'll win ten. Then l'll put it
on another horse.

370
00:21:49,130 --> 00:21:52,828
And if l use my head, and l'm lucky,
l'll run it up to five hundred bucks.

371
00:21:54,132 --> 00:21:55,791
Then you know what l'm gonna do?
- What Papa?

372
00:21:56,674 --> 00:22:02,211
l'm gonna take you on a trip. Just
you and me, on a regular train.

373
00:22:02,469 --> 00:22:05,137
Maybe we'll go down south and see
the cotton.

374
00:22:05,387 --> 00:22:08,255
You know, down where then cotton
blossoms blow?

375
00:22:08,512 --> 00:22:12,839
"Way down upon the Swannee River...

376
00:22:13,098 --> 00:22:18,801
Far, far away..." You're a nice girl,
baby.

377
00:22:19,059 --> 00:22:21,631
come on, we'll go up and tell your
Mama the news about my job.

378
00:22:28,729 --> 00:22:30,602
Anybody seen Johnny Nolan's wife?

379
00:22:30,855 --> 00:22:33,559
Johnny? You all right?

380
00:22:33,815 --> 00:22:34,846
And why not?

381
00:22:35,107 --> 00:22:37,560
Ain't l married to the most
beautiful lady in all Williamsburg

382
00:22:37,816 --> 00:22:38,597
Brooklyn?

383
00:22:38,858 --> 00:22:41,608
Well, you're shouting so that
they'll hear you over to Manhattan.

384
00:22:41,859 --> 00:22:43,566
Now, don't you get fresh with me
tonight, Mrs. Nolan.

385
00:22:43,819 --> 00:22:45,561
lt happens l'm working. Klomper's.
Big wedding party.

386
00:22:45,819 --> 00:22:47,277
Well, l thought you looked kinda
extra dressy.

387
00:22:47,529 --> 00:22:49,437
l guess you won't get home until the
sun comes up.

388
00:22:49,696 --> 00:22:50,230
The later the better.

389
00:22:50,488 --> 00:22:53,107
The more tips, the more fine silk
stockings for my wife's pretty legs.

390
00:22:53,364 --> 00:22:55,355
Oh, silk stocking's is just what l
need.

391
00:22:55,615 --> 00:22:57,073
Now, just wait a minute, Mrs. Nolan.

392
00:22:57,324 --> 00:22:58,782
Ain't you gonna give me a kiss for
luck?

393
00:22:59,033 --> 00:23:00,195
oh, the whole house is looking.

394
00:23:00,450 --> 00:23:01,564
Sure, l know they's looking, but who
cares.

395
00:23:01,826 --> 00:23:03,734
This is the finest job l've had in
months.

396
00:23:03,994 --> 00:23:05,368
Maybe l'll get more from tonight.

397
00:23:05,619 --> 00:23:07,491
Well, you'd better get on with it.
Good jobs don't wait.

398
00:23:07,744 --> 00:23:10,115
But the job's no good without your
kissing me.

399
00:23:16,332 --> 00:23:18,821
Well, you still got away with you,
Johnny Nolan.

400
00:23:19,083 --> 00:23:21,917
Now go on, get out of here.
Before you know it,

401
00:23:22,168 --> 00:23:24,289
the folks at that wedding
will be an old married couple.

402
00:23:24,543 --> 00:23:25,705
Before you know it, l won't go at
all.

403
00:23:25,960 --> 00:23:27,502
There's ain't the only wedding that
counts.

404
00:23:27,753 --> 00:23:30,503
Take your hat arid get out of here
before someone else cops that job.

405
00:23:32,046 --> 00:23:37,796
Our, ah, Francie tells me that
Sissy's gone and done it again.

406
00:23:40,299 --> 00:23:43,916
Well, maybe he's a nice fella.
Don't be too hard on her, huh?

407
00:23:44,176 --> 00:23:47,045
They was all nice fellas. Beat it?
now, Johnny.

408
00:23:48,053 --> 00:23:50,091
Well, thas just a sample, madam.

409
00:23:50,346 --> 00:23:52,751
lf you like my stock, drop me a card
and l'll be back again.

410
00:23:53,013 --> 00:23:54,127
Good evening!

411
00:23:58,182 --> 00:24:02,806
Well, would you look at our
beautiful princess tonight

412
00:24:03,059 --> 00:24:05,465
in a brand-new gown.

413
00:24:05,727 --> 00:24:06,924
ls made out of silk.

414
00:24:07,185 --> 00:24:10,268
Silk? Oh, don't you tell me that.

415
00:24:10,520 --> 00:24:13,140
This dress is made out of flower
petals and birïs wings

416
00:24:13,396 --> 00:24:15,933
and a little old piece of cloud.

417
00:24:17,606 --> 00:24:23,890
Anybody can tell that. Oh, good
evening, Mr. Spencer.

418
00:24:24,150 --> 00:24:24,896
Working tonight, Johnny?

419
00:24:25,151 --> 00:24:28,767
Yeah, big wedding party. Oh, good
evening Miss Lizzie, Miss Maggie.

420
00:24:29,027 --> 00:24:31,600
You're looking fine today,
indeed you are.

421
00:24:31,862 --> 00:24:35,810
Thank you, ladies. Here comes the
Bride. HereGood evening, ladies.

422
00:24:36,072 --> 00:24:36,439
Good evening!

423
00:24:36,698 --> 00:24:43,740
Allow me, Princess.
Hi, Mr. Ching.

424
00:24:43,992 --> 00:24:44,940
Hello.

425
00:24:45,201 --> 00:24:46,742
Was did Mom say about Aunt Sissy?

426
00:24:46,993 --> 00:24:49,364
Now don't worry about it,
everything's going to be all right.

427
00:24:49,619 --> 00:24:54,741
Your Aunt Sissy's a fine woman,
Francie. Look at them things!...

428
00:24:57,872 --> 00:25:00,444
There's no use talking. Some day l'm
gonna buy you them skates.

429
00:25:00,707 --> 00:25:02,663
Mama says not to be too late, Papa.

430
00:25:02,916 --> 00:25:05,453
Look, God invented time and when he
invents something,

431
00:25:05,709 --> 00:25:06,739
there's always plenty of it.

432
00:25:07,001 --> 00:25:08,494
There's your car, Papa.

433
00:25:08,751 --> 00:25:10,126
Boy, look at them knives!

434
00:25:10,377 --> 00:25:12,001
Mama says time is money.

435
00:25:12,253 --> 00:25:14,790
Well, l guess he wasn't worrying
much about money right then.

436
00:25:15,046 --> 00:25:16,374
There's your car, Papa.

437
00:25:16,630 --> 00:25:18,124
Well, l might as well catch it.

438
00:25:36,888 --> 00:25:37,918
Supper's ready.

439
00:25:38,180 --> 00:25:39,424
Y Hey, am l hungry!

440
00:25:39,681 --> 00:25:41,139
And when weren't you hungry?
- Mama?

441
00:25:41,390 --> 00:25:43,180
Yes, Francie.
- what does white mean?

442
00:25:43,432 --> 00:25:46,681
Oh, just white, l guess. What do you
mean, what does it mean?

443
00:25:46,934 --> 00:25:48,344
Neeley, sit down at your place.

444
00:25:48,601 --> 00:25:50,308
Well, why do girls always wear it
when they're married,

445
00:25:50,561 --> 00:25:52,136
and when they're confirmed
and when they graduate?

446
00:25:52,394 --> 00:25:54,184
Why does it always have to be white?

447
00:25:54,436 --> 00:25:57,638
Just one of those things somebody
started. Lots of things like that.

448
00:25:57,896 --> 00:25:59,769
Will l have a white dress when l
graduate?

449
00:26:00,022 --> 00:26:02,477
We'll see. Neeley will probably have
to have shoes by that time.

450
00:26:02,732 --> 00:26:03,562
But, Mama!

451
00:26:03,816 --> 00:26:04,231
Well, talk to him about it.

452
00:26:04,483 --> 00:26:07,018
lf you can get him to quit coming
through the soles of his shoes...

453
00:26:07,275 --> 00:26:08,519
Just because he's a boy.

454
00:26:08,776 --> 00:26:12,024
All right, Mama, l will gladly do
without so my little brother can be

455
00:26:12,277 --> 00:26:13,521
happy with new shoes.

456
00:26:13,778 --> 00:26:15,651
Little brother my eye...

457
00:26:15,904 --> 00:26:18,275
That will do. Francie, you read too
much.

458
00:26:19,531 --> 00:26:21,402
Hey, Aunt Sissy!
- What did you bring us?

459
00:26:21,656 --> 00:26:23,564
l brought myself chickapeas, isn't
that enough?

460
00:26:23,823 --> 00:26:25,317
Oh, and a couple of magazines from
the dentist.

461
00:26:25,574 --> 00:26:27,482
Whas he need 'em for, or me
either?

462
00:26:27,742 --> 00:26:30,231
l can't read like my educated little
niece here.

463
00:26:30,493 --> 00:26:31,358
Hello, Katie, my darling.

464
00:26:31,619 --> 00:26:35,033
Good evening, sissy.

465
00:26:39,996 --> 00:26:43,161
Well, you look fine, Katie.

466
00:26:43,415 --> 00:26:46,165
Yeah, l look fine.

467
00:26:46,416 --> 00:26:50,328
Who spilled the beans. Oh, l forgot,
it was old Barker's day here.

468
00:26:50,585 --> 00:26:53,583
Where's Johnny? l was kinda counting
on him to be in my corner.

469
00:26:53,835 --> 00:26:55,115
Oh, sure. You and Johnny.

470
00:26:55,378 --> 00:26:55,662
Oh, look, Katie.

471
00:26:55,920 --> 00:26:57,662
l didn't tell you because l wanted
to bring Bill around.

472
00:26:57,921 --> 00:27:01,086
But, l couldn't. He's home sleeping.
