01:39:19,620 --> 01:39:21,991
He was a fine man, Mrs. Nolan.

1622
01:39:27,332 --> 01:39:30,332
l'd a glad to let the children work
for you, Mr. McCarrity.

1623
01:39:30,583 --> 01:39:35,408
And the four dollars a week will
keep us until the baby comes.

1624
01:39:35,669 --> 01:39:37,707
And Francie won't have to quit
school, she can keep on,

1625
01:39:37,961 --> 01:39:38,743
and they can both...

1626
01:39:45,090 --> 01:39:46,630
Well, is a deal, then.

1627
01:39:46,881 --> 01:39:49,999
And you tell them to come through
the family entrance tomorrow after

1628
01:39:50,258 --> 01:39:53,839
school and ah...
ls that all right with you, Francie?

1629
01:39:54,093 --> 01:39:55,255
Yes.

1630
01:39:58,220 --> 01:40:03,803
Well, ah, well is settled then,
and good day to you, Mrs. Nolan.

1631
01:40:04,055 --> 01:40:08,382
And thank you again, Mr. McGarrity.
Francie?

1632
01:40:08,640 --> 01:40:09,838
Yes, Mama?

1633
01:40:12,434 --> 01:40:14,509
l'm glad you can keep on with your
school.

1634
01:40:14,768 --> 01:40:18,679
l was hoping something like this
would happen but l didn't want to

1635
01:40:18,936 --> 01:40:20,762
say anything until the time come.

1636
01:40:22,688 --> 01:40:27,098
But your Papa and l talked it all
over and there were reasons

1637
01:40:27,356 --> 01:40:30,972
and there just wasn't any other way.

1638
01:40:32,650 --> 01:40:35,981
lt doesn't matter. Papa saved one
from it.

1639
01:40:52,700 --> 01:40:53,648
Hi-ya, kid.

1640
01:40:53,909 --> 01:40:56,398
Well, they're sure taking chances l
wouldn't, leaving you handling meat.

1641
01:40:57,369 --> 01:40:58,234
Where's France.

1642
01:40:58,494 --> 01:41:04,362
Hello, kid. How are you lamb? Look,
you gotta do something for me.

1643
01:41:04,621 --> 01:41:06,529
This was in the paper and l cut it
out.

1644
01:41:06,789 --> 01:41:10,369
You got to read it to me.
Whas the matter, hon?

1645
01:41:10,624 --> 01:41:12,283
Nothing, l'm all right, Aunt Sissy.

1646
01:41:12,541 --> 01:41:14,083
No, you ain't. You ain't been since...

1647
01:41:14,334 --> 01:41:17,166
Look, don't you think you better
spill it to your Aunt Sissy?

1648
01:41:17,418 --> 01:41:19,125
What is it you want me to read to
you, Aunt Sissy?

1649
01:41:19,377 --> 01:41:22,412
Well, we'll get that out of the way
first. Look, here it is.

1650
01:41:22,670 --> 01:41:24,745
Likely you don't remember him, but
is my last husband, Bill.

1651
01:41:25,004 --> 01:41:26,546
The one l thought was dead,
but he ain't.

1652
01:41:26,797 --> 01:41:28,835
He's got his picture in there and l
want to know what it says.

1653
01:41:29,090 --> 01:41:31,164
Maybe it says where he lives so's l
can write to him about getting a

1654
01:41:31,423 --> 01:41:32,205
divorce or something.

1655
01:41:32,465 --> 01:41:34,291
l got the best husband in all the
world now,

1656
01:41:34,550 --> 01:41:36,292
and l don't want this here one
bobbing up and making no trouble.

1657
01:41:36,551 --> 01:41:39,301
He's a fireman someplace. l can tell
that from his clothes.

1658
01:41:39,552 --> 01:41:41,176
He was just starting out in the
fireman business...

1659
01:41:41,428 --> 01:41:43,051
lt says he's a hero. He saved some
people in a fire.

1660
01:41:43,304 --> 01:41:44,133
Does it say where?

1661
01:41:44,388 --> 01:41:46,674
The ninth precinct. Manhattan.

1662
01:41:46,929 --> 01:41:50,012
Manhattan, huh? Couldn't make the
grade in Brooklyn, l guess.

1663
01:41:50,264 --> 01:41:52,884
l want you to write to him, Francie.
Write this: "Dear Bill...

1664
01:41:53,141 --> 01:41:55,465
This says his name is Roland Polasky.

1665
01:41:55,725 --> 01:41:59,424
Thas right. l remember. Make it
"Dear Mr. Polasky.

1666
01:42:00,685 --> 01:42:03,353
Being's as now l'm married to
somebody else, l want you to see

1667
01:42:03,603 --> 01:42:05,262
about getting a real legal divorce.

1668
01:42:05,520 --> 01:42:07,678
Because l thought you was dead but
you ain't.

1669
01:42:07,938 --> 01:42:10,262
And because you got the money now on
account of the reward.

1670
01:42:10,523 --> 01:42:12,396
Yours very truly, Sissy." Something
like that.

1671
01:42:12,649 --> 01:42:14,687
But Aunt Sissy, he must have already
done that.

1672
01:42:14,941 --> 01:42:16,683
Because it says here he's married
again.

1673
01:42:16,941 --> 01:42:18,020
lt does?

1674
01:42:18,275 --> 01:42:20,101
"On the human interest side of the
story,

1675
01:42:20,360 --> 01:42:23,561
Mrs. Polasky had returned home only
the day before from the hospital,

1676
01:42:23,820 --> 01:42:25,977
after presenting Mr. Polasky with
a brand new son,

1677
01:42:26,237 --> 01:42:27,814
the fourth child of the marriage.

1678
01:42:28,072 --> 01:42:30,940
So, if he got a divorce that long
ago, you don't have to.

1679
01:42:31,197 --> 01:42:33,734
Then my being married to Bill, this
one l mean, is all legal?

1680
01:42:33,990 --> 01:42:36,740
Well, now, if that ain't a load off
my chest.

1681
01:42:36,991 --> 01:42:40,939
You know something, l think l'll
give Bill Polasky a wedding present.

1682
01:42:41,202 --> 01:42:43,573
But Aunt Sissy, you can't. He's been
married for years.

1683
01:42:44,619 --> 01:42:48,567
Four kids, huh? Must be a sickly
woman, this Mrs. Polasky,

1684
01:42:48,829 --> 01:42:50,572
going to the hospital just
to have a baby.

1685
01:42:50,830 --> 01:42:53,865
Oh, no, lots of people go there now
to have babies. ls better.

1686
01:42:54,124 --> 01:42:57,372
Sure enough? You know something?

1687
01:42:57,625 --> 01:43:01,240
l'm gonna cash in my funeral policy
and have my baby at a hospital.

1688
01:43:01,501 --> 01:43:03,991
And when my baby is born, and lives,

1689
01:43:05,211 --> 01:43:07,167
l want you to write that R. Polasky
and announce it.

1690
01:43:08,254 --> 01:43:09,368
Boy do l feel better.

1691
01:43:09,630 --> 01:43:11,207
And now, chickapea, we'll talk about
you.

1692
01:43:11,464 --> 01:43:13,171
Can't your Aunt Sissy help you any?

1693
01:43:13,423 --> 01:43:14,123
l'm all right.

1694
01:43:14,382 --> 01:43:15,127
No, you aren't honey.

1695
01:43:15,381 --> 01:43:16,839
Not all shut up like that, l know
how you feel,

1696
01:43:17,091 --> 01:43:18,205
but you can't keep hanging on to it.

1697
01:43:18,466 --> 01:43:23,291
l'm ail right. l don't want to talk
about it.

1698
01:43:23,552 --> 01:43:23,919
All right, baby. All right. But l'll
tell you what.

1699
01:43:24,177 --> 01:43:25,884
You can do something for me.

1700
01:43:26,137 --> 01:43:31,423
Look, your Mama feels awful bad too.
She needs you.

1701
01:43:31,680 --> 01:43:33,303
Why don't you talk to her about it.

1702
01:43:33,597 --> 01:43:35,055
She doesn't need me.
No she doesn't.

1703
01:43:35,306 --> 01:43:36,053
She's got Neeley!

1704
01:43:36,307 --> 01:43:37,884
Why wasn't it Neeley she was going
to make quit school.

1705
01:43:38,141 --> 01:43:39,006
He never cared about it.

1706
01:43:39,267 --> 01:43:40,677
She doesn't love me like Papa did.

1707
01:43:40,934 --> 01:43:42,593
And she didn't love him, either. Not
really.

1708
01:43:42,852 --> 01:43:45,803
She hurt him, l saw her. And he
never hurt anybody.

1709
01:43:46,102 --> 01:43:48,509
l'm gonna finish this grade because
he gave it to me

1710
01:43:48,770 --> 01:43:49,968
and then l'll work for her.

1711
01:43:50,229 --> 01:43:52,434
But she can't be Papa to me, she
can't ever!

1712
01:43:52,689 --> 01:43:53,684
Don't feel like that, baby, don't.

1713
01:43:53,939 --> 01:43:58,599
Leave me alone. l'm all right.
Please go away and leave me alone.

1714
01:44:01,442 --> 01:44:04,110
All right, chickapea, all right.

1715
01:44:12,197 --> 01:44:13,571
Ah, Mr. Sterns...
Yes, sir.

1716
01:44:19,199 --> 01:44:20,230
Francie...

1717
01:44:21,658 --> 01:44:22,488
Yes, Mama?

1718
01:44:25,619 --> 01:44:26,898
l want to talk to you, Francie.

1719
01:44:32,037 --> 01:44:33,068
Yes, Mama?

1720
01:44:33,913 --> 01:44:38,205
lt isn't going to be long now, for
me, l mean, for my baby.

1721
01:44:38,457 --> 01:44:40,745
We can't come to a hospital.

1722
01:44:41,000 --> 01:44:44,580
There isn't even going to be enough
money for a woman to come and help.

1723
01:44:46,835 --> 01:44:52,039
l'm going to need you, Francie.
Don't ever be far away.

1724
01:44:52,296 --> 01:44:55,829
Neeley's, well, a boy ain't much
good at a time like this.

1725
01:44:56,089 --> 01:45:00,878
l'm counting on you, Francie.
You won't forget that, will you?

1726
01:45:02,841 --> 01:45:06,125
All right, Mama. l'll remember.

1727
01:45:06,385 --> 01:45:08,341
Which one of you is Mr. Steven
Edwards?

1728
01:45:08,594 --> 01:45:09,673
Thas me.

1729
01:45:10,512 --> 01:45:12,254
Well, there are three in your family
now.

1730
01:45:12,513 --> 01:45:13,970
You are the father of a pretty fine
boy.

1731
01:45:14,221 --> 01:45:15,299
ls he alive?
- Very much so.

1732
01:45:15,555 --> 01:45:18,223
He was a little reluctant about it
at first, l had to rouse him with a

1733
01:45:18,473 --> 01:45:20,595
little oxygen, now he's mad at me,
you ought to hear him.

1734
01:45:20,849 --> 01:45:22,011
l've got to see him.

1735
01:45:22,266 --> 01:45:24,092
Well, neither one of them are quite
up to a visit just now,

1736
01:45:24,351 --> 01:45:25,548
in a little while.

1737
01:45:25,810 --> 01:45:29,886
The learning. The learning that
saved that baby.

1738
01:45:30,144 --> 01:45:31,602
Thas fine, Bill.

1739
01:45:32,645 --> 01:45:34,055
Where are you going, Uncle Bill?

1740
01:45:34,313 --> 01:45:36,020
l'm going out and get some
strawberry ice cream

1741
01:45:36,272 --> 01:45:39,307
and a rattle for my son.
And whas more, my name ain't Bill.

1742
01:45:39,690 --> 01:45:42,227
ls Steve, do you hear that? l'm a
Papa and my name's Steve.

1743
01:45:42,483 --> 01:45:47,604
And is Uncle Steve, too. Steve,
Steve...

1744
01:45:49,110 --> 01:45:51,267
So, we have a man in the family.

1745
01:45:58,697 --> 01:45:59,941
Quick as we see she's all right,

1746
01:46:00,198 --> 01:46:02,236
you go on up to McGarrity's and
see if you can do my work, too.

1747
01:46:02,490 --> 01:46:04,281
l'm going to finish the scrubbing
for her.

1748
01:46:04,533 --> 01:46:05,647
She oughtn't do any more.

1749
01:46:05,909 --> 01:46:11,908
She wasn't feeling good this morning.
Mama!

1750
01:46:19,914 --> 01:46:20,696
Mama!

1751
01:46:21,998 --> 01:46:23,373
ln here, Frances.

1752
01:46:30,960 --> 01:46:31,955
You all right, Mama?

1753
01:46:37,797 --> 01:46:40,962
Give Neeley a nickel to go after
Grandma and Sissy.

1754
01:46:42,007 --> 01:46:43,713
He can walk home after.

1755
01:46:44,549 --> 01:46:46,505
Get me a nightgown in that bottom
drawer.

1756
01:46:53,928 --> 01:46:56,050
Hurry, don't stand there staring.

1757
01:47:04,640 --> 01:47:05,470
ls she going to die?

1758
01:47:05,724 --> 01:47:08,558
Of course not, is the baby. You
heard what Mama said, and hurry.

1759
01:47:08,809 --> 01:47:11,133
And don't forget stopping at
McGarrity's on the way back.

1760
01:47:11,394 --> 01:47:23,226
We can't lose the work. She only
wants me now. Mama!

1761
01:47:24,524 --> 01:47:28,187
What is it?
Oh, l'll be there in a minute.

1762
01:47:54,786 --> 01:47:57,323
You're taking real good care of me,
Francie.

1763
01:47:58,745 --> 01:48:00,120
Am l, Mama?

1764
01:48:14,043 --> 01:48:15,418
Umm. Tastes good.

1765
01:48:25,006 --> 01:48:26,832
Can l get you a glass of water,
Mama?

1766
01:48:27,841 --> 01:48:29,583
When l want something,
l'll ask for it.

1767
01:48:29,841 --> 01:48:31,216
Yes, Mama.

1768
01:48:33,218 --> 01:48:36,300
Don't just stand there and throw
questions at me, l'm too tired.

1769
01:48:36,552 --> 01:48:39,718
You'd better have some coffee too.

1770
01:48:39,971 --> 01:48:42,840
Mama, even if Neeley is a boy,
wouldn't you rather have him here?

1771
01:48:43,096 --> 01:48:44,471
He's always such a comfort to you.

1772
01:48:44,722 --> 01:48:46,429
No, is you thas a comfort now.
What time is it?

1773
01:48:46,681 --> 01:48:47,676
l don't know, Mama.

1774
01:48:47,932 --> 01:48:48,880
Get the clock.

1775
01:48:58,769 --> 01:49:00,144
one minute to Mama.

1776
01:49:00,395 --> 01:49:02,517
Are you sure it isn't slow?

1777
01:49:02,771 --> 01:49:04,051
No, Mama.

1778
01:49:04,313 --> 01:49:06,637
Maybe is fast, then.

1779
01:49:06,898 --> 01:49:10,230
l'll look at the jeweler's clock out
the parlor window.

1780
01:49:16,193 --> 01:49:25,227
That candle's pretty, like Christmas.
That was the night l told him.

1781
01:49:33,492 --> 01:49:35,614
ls nice having a visit from my
daughter.

1782
01:49:39,078 --> 01:49:41,650
l didn't want for you to have to
grow up so soon.

1783
01:49:42,579 --> 01:49:44,866
l didn't want for you to have to
quit school.

1784
01:49:45,121 --> 01:49:46,663
l tried to tell him that.

1785
01:49:46,914 --> 01:49:49,036
He didn't mind about the baby, but
he never forgived me

1786
01:49:49,290 --> 01:49:50,867
for wanting you to quit school.

1787
01:49:51,124 --> 01:49:58,083
l told him and he just went out. You
never forgived me, either.

1788
01:49:58,335 --> 01:49:59,497
Please don't, Mama.

1789
01:49:59,752 --> 01:50:01,329
He would have bought you dolls
instead of milk.

1790
01:50:01,586 --> 01:50:04,420
l don't know, maybe you would have
been happier. l don't know.

1791
01:50:04,671 --> 01:50:07,624
l never woulïve thought of giving
you that school, like he did.

1792
01:50:07,881 --> 01:50:12,835
And all them fine compositions of
yours. l never read one of 'em.

1793
01:50:13,091 --> 01:50:17,631
l shoulda had time. Johnny did.
But l couldn't do no different.

1794
01:50:17,885 --> 01:50:19,841
l don't know how l could do any
different.

1795
01:50:27,722 --> 01:50:28,919
What time is it?

1796
01:50:30,014 --> 01:50:31,721
One minute after four, Mama.

1797
01:50:33,683 --> 01:50:36,172
Rinse a cloth out in cold water,
wipe my face.

1798
01:50:48,772 --> 01:50:50,645
Don't let her die, please!

1799
01:51:06,821 --> 01:51:10,651
Mama, what if the baby comes before
Grandma and Aunt Sissy get here?

1800
01:51:11,323 --> 01:51:13,646
You can see l couldn't do no
different, can't you?

1801
01:51:15,116 --> 01:51:16,574
Neeley, he don't like school.

1802
01:51:16,825 --> 01:51:18,615
lf he'd quit, he'd never go back
again.

1803
01:51:19,368 --> 01:51:21,692
But you, no matter what happens,
you'd find a way to go back,

1804
01:51:21,952 --> 01:51:25,035
you'd fight to go back.
You can see that, can't you?

1805
01:51:26,496 --> 01:51:30,573
l... Yes, Mama.

1806
01:51:32,081 --> 01:51:34,653
Read me something, Francie.
- Yes, Mama.

1807
01:51:35,833 --> 01:51:37,243
Read me one of your compositions.

1808
01:51:37,500 --> 01:51:39,326
l ain't never read any of your
compositions.

1809
01:51:39,585 --> 01:51:41,244
ls on my conscience.

1810
01:51:46,378 --> 01:51:48,500
l tore all those up.

1811
01:51:48,754 --> 01:51:52,122
No, you didn't. Not all of'em.

1812
01:51:54,507 --> 01:51:57,210
Can't l read you Shakespeare? ls
much better.

1813
01:51:59,300 --> 01:52:01,173
Read "Twas on a Night Like This".

1814
01:52:01,426 --> 01:52:05,801
l'd like to have something pretty on
my mind. Sit by the candle.

1815
01:52:15,432 --> 01:52:18,301
"The moon shines bright,
in such a night as this,

1816
01:52:18,558 --> 01:52:21,261
when the sweet wind did
gently kiss the trees..."

1817
01:52:21,518 --> 01:52:24,683
Say, did you ever find out who
Troylis was and Cressida?

1818
01:52:24,936 --> 01:52:26,346
Yes, Mama, Troylis was...

1819
01:52:26,604 --> 01:52:30,301
Some other day when l got time. Read
me one of your compositions now.

1820
01:52:30,563 --> 01:52:32,305
You won't like them, Mama.

1821
01:52:32,564 --> 01:52:33,843
You thought about them, and you
worked on them,

1822
01:52:34,106 --> 01:52:37,224
and you got good marks on them.
Get 'em, l said.

1823
01:53:11,621 --> 01:53:17,987
Sit here. Go on.

1824
01:53:21,417 --> 01:53:29,241
ls called, "The Man People Loved".
Please don't make me do this, Mama.

1825
01:53:29,503 --> 01:53:30,285
Read it.

1826
01:53:34,047 --> 01:53:38,790
"Perhaps many people might have said
of him that he was a failure.

1827
01:53:39,049 --> 01:53:42,462
lt is true that he had no gift for
making money,

1828
01:53:42,716 --> 01:53:46,926
but he had a gift for laughter,
and for making people love him.

1829
01:53:47,761 --> 01:53:51,377
He had the gift of making you feel
proud to walk down the street with him

1830
01:53:51,637 --> 01:53:54,127
He had nothing to give but himself.

1831
01:53:54,389 --> 01:53:57,422
But of this he gave generously, like
a king.

1832
01:53:57,681 --> 01:54:02,056
Like a king. Thas like it was.

1833
01:54:02,308 --> 01:54:05,473
Walking down the street with him,
you always felt like that.

1834
01:54:06,477 --> 01:54:08,184
Did you, Mama.

1835
01:54:08,894 --> 01:54:11,727
You were real smart to write it down
like that, Francie.

1836
01:54:11,978 --> 01:54:21,641
Thas like it was. Francie, l miss
him so much!

1837
01:54:21,899 --> 01:54:28,776
lf the baby's a boy, we'll call him
Johnny. Where's Sissy?

1838
01:54:29,027 --> 01:54:36,438
Neeley's been gone a long time. Wipe
my face.

1839
01:54:36,697 --> 01:54:38,238
No, don't let go of my hand.

1840
01:54:40,324 --> 01:54:44,567
lf is a girl, we'll call her Annie
Lorrie.

1841
01:54:44,825 --> 01:54:48,821
Remember that tune he played? You
ought to have piano lessons.

1842
01:54:49,077 --> 01:54:50,654
l'll see if l can manage.

1843
01:54:50,911 --> 01:54:53,910
You won't forget to dust the piano,
will you Francie?

1844
01:54:54,163 --> 01:54:56,651
Who'll cry for me like that if l
died?

1845
01:54:56,913 --> 01:55:00,327
l never did a wrong thing in my life,
but it ain't enough.

1846
01:55:00,581 --> 01:55:04,992
Oh! Sissy, l didn't mean to be hard,
